%[text] # Create Data Center Model for HVAC Load Analysis
%[text] Copyright 2025 - 2026 The MathWorks, Inc.
%[text:tableOfContents]{"heading":"Table of Contents"}
%[text] ## Create Data Center Model
%[text] %[text:anchor:TMP_3695] This workflow shows how to create a data center model to analyze the HVAC load. Data centers produce a significant heat load that needs to be cooled for optimal performance. Data center installation and operation is expensive and often an estimate for data center thermal management is required before planning.
%[text] ### Data Center Physical Layout
%[text] A typical data center has multiple power distribution units (PDU). Each PDU consists of multiple CPU servers. The server load or utilization can change depending on requirements. Most data centers are housed in a large room or enclosure. The room typically has four walls. Data centers can be cooled using HVAC or liquid cooling methods. This example uses HVAC to cool the data center.
%[text] ![](text:image:689a)
%[text] The picture shows a top view of a data center with multiple PDUs connected in the 'x' and 'y' direction. Custom libraries for the walls and room model the data center layout. You need to estimate the solar load on a data center to efficiently cool it. This model assumes that the room is a south facing room in the northern hemisphere. Positive x denotes east, negative x denotes west, positive y denotes north, and negative y denotes south direction. 
%[text] ![](text:image:5971)
%[text] A rectangular room with multiple PDU units represents the physical layout. Rotate the room by a certain angle to model orientation effects. This example assumes that the roof is a flat surface. The data center consists of multiple PDU units, stagnant air inside the room, data center room walls, doors, and windows. The custom libraries for building a room are present in `Simscape Custom Libraries / Building Components` and the solar libraries in the `Simscape Custom Libraries / Solar Radiation` section of the `Simulink Browser`.
%[text] ### Build Components
%[text] In this example, the custom component Data Center `Server Unit` from the `Simscape Custom Libraries` models the data center PDUs. The Data Center `Server Unit` component models electrical load estimation and heat generation in the PDU, based on server name-plate-parameterization. The heat generation and electrical load change with PDU utilization, specified by port **U**.
%[text] ![](text:image:2d74)
%[text] Multiple Data Center `Server Unit` components must be connected with each other to build a data center. Library elements from `Building Components` define the data center room. You can use the `createDataCenterWithEnclosure` function to build the data center model programmatically. In this example, a 20 kW data center is created using 12 (4 in x and 3 in y direction) Data Center `Server Unit` custom library components. The data center room has length 12m (in x direction), width 8m (in y direction), and height 3m (in z direction). The volume of air between the data center walls and servers is 8% of the total room volume. The data center component model is saved to the file name specified by the `DatacenterModelName` parameter.  Edit and run the code below to change the data center configuration.
%[text] ```matlabCodeExample
%[text] % Specify name of the model.
%[text] DatacenterModelName = "MyDatacenterModelLib";
%[text] % Specify path to save the model library files
%[text] libFileSavePath = fullfile(currentProject().RootFolder,"Workflow","HVAC","CreateDatacenterForUtilizationAnalysis");
%[text] % Specify server name plate data for the data center
%[text] serverData = getDataCenterNamePlateRatingTable(Display=true);
%[text] % Create data center
%[text] createDataCenterWithEnclosure(NumPDUunitsX=3,NumPDUunitsY=4,...
%[text]     ModelName=DatacenterModelName,...
%[text]     ModelOption="Thermal",...
%[text]     RatingDatacenter=simscape.Value(20,"kW"),...
%[text]     ServerNamePlateRating=serverData.nameplateRating,...
%[text]     ServerPowerSystemSpec=serverData.powerSystemSpecs,...
%[text]     ThermalRes=simscape.Value(0.01,"K/W"),...
%[text]     EnclosureName="Room",...
%[text]     PercentAirVolInRoom=8,...
%[text]     RoomLength=simscape.Value(12,"m"),...
%[text]     RoomWidth=simscape.Value(8,"m"),...
%[text]     RoomHeight=simscape.Value(3,"m"),...
%[text]     RoomRotate=simscape.Value(25,"deg"),...
%[text]     WallThickness=simscape.Value(0.05,"m"),...
%[text]     Diagnostics=true,...
%[text]     SaveAtFullPath=libFileSavePath);
%[text] ```
%[text] ### Assemble the Model
%[text] The data center model is stored in the file `MyDatacenterModel_lib`. Copy the contents onto a fresh canvas or your model canvas and connect the ports to complete the system. In this example, the data center connects to a **Controls** block which provides heat to the data center through the port **Q**. The **Controls** block measures the data center room temperature and brings it close to the desired set point temperature, `Tset`. The heat provided to cool the data center helps you estimate cooling requirements under various different operational conditions. The ambient conditions are defined by the `Solar Radiation (LUT)` block and the `Temperature Source (LUT)` block. The `HVAC_Switch` can be 0 or 1. When set to 1, the HVAC operation is modeled. When set to 0, HVAC is not modeled and the output of port **Q** in the **Controls** block is zero.
%[text] ![](text:image:81f6)
%[text] Open the model to begin setup for analysis.
modelParam.mdlName = "DatacenterUtilization"; 
open_system(modelParam.mdlName);
%[text] Load the data struct saved as a MAT file during the data center component creation step.
modelParam.lib = load("MyDatacenterModelLib");
%[text] ## Define Parameters
%[text] ### Location and Datetime
%[text] Specify location and duration for analysis.
modelParam.geoLocation = getGeoLocationForMajorCities(CityName="Bengaluru");
modelParam.tStart = datetime(2025,1,1,1,0,0);
modelParam.tEnd = datetime(2025,4,1,1,0,0);
%[text] Add the location and datetime parameters to all relevant blocks in the model.
specifyModelLocationAndDateTime(ModelName=modelParam.mdlName,... %[output:group:8f94989d] %[output:080e709c]
                                Location=modelParam.geoLocation,... %[output:080e709c]
                                StartTime=modelParam.tStart,... %[output:080e709c]
                                EndTime=modelParam.tEnd,... %[output:080e709c]
                                DayLightSavingHrs=0,... %[output:080e709c]
                                Diagnostics=true); %[output:group:8f94989d] %[output:080e709c]
%%
%[text] ### Server Utilization
%[text] Specify each PDU utilization value, between 0 - 1. 
modelParam.sizePDU = size(modelParam.lib.datacenter.Servers.Name);
modelParam.utilServer = [0.48 0.51 0.37 0.44; ...
                         0.42 0.52 0.33 0.41; ...
                         0.45 0.58 0.39 0.41];
if ~and(size(modelParam.utilServer,1)==modelParam.sizePDU(1,1),size(modelParam.utilServer,2)==modelParam.sizePDU(1,2))
    disp(strcat("ERROR : Utilization matrix size must be = ",mat2str(modelParam.sizePDU)));
end
set_param(modelParam.mdlName+"/Controls/ServerUtil","Constant",...
    mat2str(reshape(modelParam.utilServer,[1,modelParam.sizePDU(1,1)*modelParam.sizePDU(1,2)])));
%%
%[text] ### Update HVAC Model
%[text] Update the model with HVAC parameters.
modelParam.thermalConductance = 25000; % [W/K]
modelParam.heatExchangeCap = 100000;   % [W]
set_param(modelParam.mdlName+"/Controls/Thermal Conductance","Gain",num2str(modelParam.thermalConductance));
set_param(modelParam.mdlName+"/Controls/Heat Exchanger Capacity","UpperLimit",num2str(modelParam.heatExchangeCap));
set_param(modelParam.mdlName+"/Controls/Heat Exchanger Capacity","LowerLimit",num2str(-modelParam.heatExchangeCap));
%[text] ### Daily Ambient Temperature
%[text] Specify ambient temperature values for all the days defined in the **datetime** vector.
modelParam.dayT = 309*ones(1,ceil(hours(modelParam.tEnd-modelParam.tStart)/24)+1);
modelParam.nightT = 301*ones(1,ceil(hours(modelParam.tEnd-modelParam.tStart)/24)+1);
%%
%[text] ## Simulate the Model
%[text] Setup the model for simulation.
set_param(modelParam.mdlName,"stoptime",num2str(seconds(modelParam.tEnd-modelParam.tStart)));
set_param(modelParam.mdlName+"/Temperature Source (LUT)","avgDayTvec",mat2str(modelParam.dayT));
set_param(modelParam.mdlName+"/Temperature Source (LUT)","avgNightTvec",mat2str(modelParam.nightT));
%[text] Simulate the model.
sim(modelParam.mdlName);
%%
%[text] ## Analyze the Results
%[text] Plot the ambient temperature.
figure("Name","Ambient Temperature Plot");
plot(simlogDatacenterUtilization.Temperature_Source_LUT.H.T); %[output:24f72e17]
%[text] Plot temperatures of all PDU units.
figure("Name","Server Unit Temperature Plot");
plot(simlogDatacenterUtilization.Datacenter.Datacenter.ServerUnits.Tvec); %[output:9bcae88f]
%[text] Calculate the HVAC requirement for the data center operation.
modelRes.Qnet = simlogDatacenterUtilization.Controls.Q.series.values;
modelRes.Time = simlogDatacenterUtilization.Controls.Q.series.time;
modelRes.AvgP = sum(modelRes.Qnet(2:end).*diff(modelRes.Time))/modelRes.Time(end);
if modelRes.AvgP > 0 %[output:group:8bf2265e]
    disp(strcat("*** Average Heating Requirement = ",num2str(round(abs(modelRes.AvgP)/1000,2)),"kW."));
else
    disp(strcat("*** Average Cooling Requirement = ",num2str(round(abs(modelRes.AvgP)/1000,2)),"kW.")); %[output:501f6c6c]
end %[output:group:8bf2265e]
%[text] 

